1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Bb4 7. Qd3 Qa5 { The first novel move. It doesn't appear to do anything except misplace my bishop. } (7... Qc7 8. a3 Bxc3+ 9. Qxc3 { I knew a bit about this theory. } 9... Nxe4?? 10. Nb5!) (7... Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 $16) 8. Bd2 Qc7 9. a3 Bc5 10. Nb3 (10. b4 Bxd4 11. Qxd4 Nc6 { I knew this was good for me, but I was somehow searching for more. }) 10... Ba7 11. Be2 d6 12. O-O Nbd7 { I felt extremely confident that this was better for white, but I was afraid of Ne5 winning my c pawn. } 13. Bf4! (13. Qg3! { This is obviously where the queen belongs. And defending g7 now becomes a huge chore for black. } 13... Qb6 14. Bd1! O-O 15. Bh6 Ne8 { White's advantage is obvious. }) 13... e5?! { Big hole on d5 should be immediately pounced on. } 14. Bd2?! (14. Bg3 { The bishop is temporarily blunted on this diagonal, but Bh4 in the future might be annoying and right now it supports the f4 break without getting in the way of the rooks on the open d file. }) 14... Qb6 15. Qc2 (15. Nd5 Nxd5 16. cxd5 { I didn't want to plug up my hole so quickly, so I figured I would first defend black's threats and then push forward. }) 15... Qd8 16. Rad1 h6 17. Kh1 O-O 18. f4 Bd4?! { Giving up your bishop for the weak b3 knight cannot be good, but I failed to find the correct way to capitalize. } 19. Nxd4 (19. Be1! Be3 20. fxe5 Nxe5 (20... dxe5 21. Rxf6! Qxf6 22. Nd5) 21. Rxf6! Qxf6 22. Nd5) 19... exd4 20. Nd5 Re8 21. Bf3 { Desperately trying to keep everything under control, but at this point, spicy tactics are called for. } (21. Bb4 Nc5 (21... Nxe4 22. Rxd4) 22. Rxd4 Ncxe4 23. Nxf6+ Nxf6 24. Rxd6 $16) (21. Nxf6+ Nxf6 22. Bf3 Qe7 23. Rfe1 $16 Ng4 24. Re2 { [%cal Gd2e1,Ge1f2,Gf2d4] }) 21... Nc5 22. Rde1 Nxd5 23. cxd5 Bd7! { Such a simple move, but now black has ample counterplay on my weakened queenside light squares. } 24. b3? (24. b4?! Ba4 25. Qb2 Nd3 26. Qxd4 Nxe1 27. Rxe1 { I didn't want to play this, but I now believe this was my best try at this point. }) 24... Bb5 25. Rg1 Nd3 26. Ref1 Rc8 27. Qb1 Nc5! { Brutal. Now e4 will fall after Bd3. All my pieces are poorly placed and my opponent immediately capitalized. } *


