1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 d6? { I've faced this before from people who don't know any Sicilian theory. Finally I found the best way forward. } 4. d5 Ne5 5. Nxe5 dxe5 6. Be2 (6. Qh5 Qc7 7. Bb5+ Bd7 8. Bxd7+ Kxd7 (8... Qxd7 9. Qxe5) 9. Qxf7 { White wins e5 very quickly after Qh5! }) 6... Nf6 7. Nc3 { We're basically in a Czech-benoni structure now, but white is ahead a tempo. } 7... Bd7 8. O-O Qc7 9. a4 { Assuming e4 is protected, I had thoughts of a Bb5 or Nb5 move. } 9... g6 10. f4 { Time to blast open the center! } 10... O-O-O?! { This wasn't on my radar at all, but now I realized that there was a lot of counterplay black could rustle up if I got too greedy taking the f, g, and h pawns. } 11. Kh1 { [%cal Gb6g1] } 11... Bg7 12. fxe5 Qxe5 13. Bf4 { The queen is almost trapped, but I felt there had to be something with my mobile pawn center... } 13... Qd4 14. e5! Nh5 15. Bxh5 gxh5 16. Qxh5 Rdf8 17. Qg5 { Honing in on a few weaknesses in black's camp. I didn't want to take the "free" f7 pawn though because of Rf8 x-raying my bishop. } { [%csl Ge7,Gg7] } 17... Rhg8 18. Rad1 { I felt this was kicking the queen to a less crucial square (not eyeing up e5), but I saw it was gonna get hairy. } 18... Qc4 (18... Bf6!?) (18... Qb4 19. Qxe7 Re8 20. Qd6 { I saw this position, but missed Bf8! } 20... Bf8 { The only move that holds it together. }) 19. Qxe7 Bxa4?? 20. e6! { Amazingly, mate on c7 is unavoidable. } 20... Bxc3 (20... Qxf4 { Best resistance. } 21. Rxf4 Be5 22. Nxa4 Rd8 (22... Bc7 23. d6 Bxd6 24. Rxd6 Re8 25. exf7 Rxe7 26. fxg8=Q+ Re8 27. Qxe8+ Kc7 28. Qd8#) 23. Rxf7 Rxd5 24. Qxb7+ Kd8 25. Rxd5+ Ke8 26. Qd7#) 21. Qc7# *


