1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bd2 c5 5. dxc5 Bxc5 6. e3 O-O 7. Nf3 { White has played the opening somewhat passively, so I begin preparations to accept the isolated d pawn, viewing it more as a dynamic strength than a static weakness. } 7... Nc6 8. a3 d5!? 9. cxd5 (9. b4 Bd6 10. cxd5 exd5 { Reaching a position that's the same as in the game. }) 9... exd5 10. b4 Bd6 11. Nd4 (11. b5? Ne5 { I'm never afraid of b5 as it allows my knight to jump further into the attack. }) 11... Re8 { [%cal Gc6d4] } (11... Nxd4 12. exd4 Re8+ 13. Be2 Bg4 14. O-O Bxe2 15. Nxe2 Rc8 { Black has a slight advantage in this forcing line, but I wanted more. }) 12. Bb5?? Nxd4! 13. Bxe8 Qxe8 { Winning two pieces for the rook would be fine under normal circumstances, but here, all 4 of my pieces are active while both of white's rooks are incredibly passive. Black is much better. } 14. O-O Nc6?! { There's really no reason to retreat here, but I figured getting in d4 would activate my remaining pieces and keep the advantage (even if it's objectively worse than the computer attacking line). } (14... Bg4! 15. f3 Qe5!! 16. f4 Qh5 17. Qb1 Ne2+ 18. Nxe2 Bxe2 19. Re1 Ne4 { Black's pieces flood into the attack with best play. }) 15. Qb3 d4 (15... Bxh2+ 16. Kxh2 Qe5+ 17. Kg1 Ng4 { A better version than in the game. Sadly I didn't see this attack until one move later. }) 16. Ne2 Bxh2+?! { It looks fun, but ultimately it's a bit too early for the sacrifices. Ne4 and Be6 were obviously more solid. } (16... Ne4 17. Rad1 Bg4!? (17... Be6 18. Qd3 Bf5) 18. f3 Nxd2 19. Rxd2 Be6 20. Qd3 Bc4! $17) 17. Kxh2 Ng4+ 18. Kg1 Qe5 19. Ng3 dxe3? (19... Be6 20. Qd3 Qg5 { Stops the one defensive idea that white has in this position. }) 20. Bxe3 { Releasing the tension was bad. I miscalculated and thought that white could not defend both the bishop and knight after Be6. } 20... Be6 21. Qd3 Rd8 22. Qe2 Qf6 { White is now completely fine, so in a desperate attempt to complicate further, I go for a knight and queen sortie near the king. } 23. f3? { And white crumbles. } (23. Rad1 Qh4 24. Rxd8+ Nxd8 25. Rd1 $16 { White is completely safe, and black's pieces are now uncoordinated. }) 23... Nd4!! { White's queen is trapped! } { [%csl Ga2,Ga6,Gb5,Gc4,Gf2,Gc2,Ge2] } 24. Bxd4 (24. Qb2 Nxf3+) (24. Qd2 Nxf3+ 25. Rxf3 Qxa1+ 26. Rf1 Rxd2 27. Rxa1 Nxe3 $19) (24. Qd3 Nxf3+) (24. Qd1 Nxe3) (24. Qe1 Nxe3 25. Qxe3 Nc2) 24... Qxd4+ 25. Kh1 Bc4! 26. Rad1?? (26. Qe4 Nf2+ 27. Rxf2 Qxa1+ 28. Kh2 { White's best try, but black has good coordination and the favorable bishop. }) 26... Qxd1! 27. Rxd1 Rxd1+ 28. Qxd1 Nf2+ 29. Kh2 Nxd1 { Black goes up a piece in an easily winning endgame. } *


