1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 5. Bd3 e6 (5... Qxd4 6. Nf3 Qd8 7. Qe2 { Do I really want to go into this line? The only move here is Bxe4 to avoid all the smothered mate threats. } 7... Bxe4 8. Bxe4 Nf6 $15) 6. c3 Nd7 7. Nf3 Bxe4 (7... Ngf6 8. Nxf6+ Qxf6 9. Bg5 Qg6 10. Bxf5 Qxf5 { The only way to avoid doubled f pawns. I didn't like my queens position during the game, but looking at it again, the 5th rank is suprisingly open for the queen to maneuver in. }) 8. Bxe4 Ngf6 9. Bd3 Be7 10. Bf4 O-O 11. O-O c5 { Black needs to break out somehow, and this is the only move that makes any sense. } 12. Re1 Nh5?! { Misplaces the bishop only temporarily... } 13. Bd2 cxd4 14. Nxd4 { [%cal Gd1h5] } 14... Nhf6 15. Qc2?! Nc5 16. Be2?! { Always play Bf1. On e2, the bishop blocks the rook from directly seeing e4. On f1, g3 followed by Bg2 puts a lot of pressure on the long diagonal. } 16... Rc8 17. Rad1 a6 { [%cal Gd4b5] } 18. b4? { Allows the knight to jump forward and forcibly win the bishop pair. } 18... Nce4 19. Bf3 Nxd2 (19... Qxd4! 20. cxd4 (20. Bxe4 Nxe4 21. Rxe4 Qd5) 20... Rxc2 21. Bxe4 Rxd2 22. Rxd2 Bxb4) 20. Rxd2 Qc7 21. Rc1 Rfd8 (21... Nd7 { Slightly more precise. Ne5 is coming soon which will either misplace the bishop or allow the knight to blockade on the c4 square. } { [%csl Ge5][%cal Ge5c4,Ge5f3] }) 22. a3 b5?? (22... Nd5!? 23. c4? Bg5!) 23. Nc6! { White's knight becomes an absolute monster on c6. } 23... Rxd2 24. Qxd2 Bd6 { [%csl Gf4] } (24... Nd5 { The best move, but not a good one. Black is barely fighting for a draw in this position after all of the trades. }) 25. g3 Nd7 { A good idea, but tactically, it just doesn't work out. } 26. Rd1 Ne5 27. Bg2?? { But white fails to take advantage of the mistake. } (27. Qxd6 Nxf3+ 28. Kg2 Qxd6 (28... Qxc6 29. Qxc6 Rxc6 30. Rd8#) 29. Rxd6 { White has two threats which cannot both be parried. } { [%cal Gc6e7,Gg2f3] }) 27... Bf8!? (27... Nxc6?! 28. Qxd6 { Black's knight looks more like a target than a contributing piece. }) 28. Nxe5 Qxe5 29. Bb7 Rxc3 30. Bxa6 Rxa3 31. Bb7 { In order to fight for a win here, black must keep all the pieces on the board and go for an attack against white's king. Rather than continue to play this long game, I decided to call it a day and simplify into a clearly drawn endgame. } 31... Ra1 32. Rxa1 Qxa1+ 33. Kg2 Qe5 { If black wants to win the b pawn, he'll have to go into an opposite-colored bishop ending. There is no attack on white's king, so the game is a draw. } *


