1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bb5+?! { White usually does not want to trade this bishop (assuming his pawns go on d4 and c3), so this is a step in the wrong direction. } 4... Nc6 5. d3 Nf6 6. O-O Bg4 { This pin makes more sense once h6-g5 is off the table due to white castling kingside. } 7. Be3 e6 8. Nbd2 Be7 (8... Bd6!? { A more aggressive square. The pin Bg5 is not threatening as it would mean that white has moved his bishop twice. The only reason I stayed away from this line is c4 - trying to take advantage of the disconnect between my queen and the d5/d3 squares. } 9. c4 O-O) 9. c3 O-O 10. Qc2 Bh5 (10... a6? 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Ne5 { I wanted to win the bishop pair, not trade bishops. } { [%csl Gg4,Gc6] }) 11. b4 a6 (11... a5! { This prying open move works when the bishop is in front of the b pawn. See: IM Rosen vs IM Klimenko on 4/25/19. } 12. a3 (12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. a3 Nd7 { Prevents the dark squared bishop trade, and so black retains the bishop pair. } 14. Nd4 Qc7 15. b5 c5 16. Nc6 Bd6 17. h3)) 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. Nd4 Qc7 14. Qa4? { This temporary piece pressure on c6 is not an inconvenience. Instead, white wants to be long term be playing a4 and pushing through the queenside majority. } 14... Rfc8 15. N2b3 e5?! { A tactical sequence to win a pawn. But it's not as strong as building up the static advantage I already have. } (15... Bg6 16. Rfd1 e5 17. Ne2 { Keeping the bishop pair and the static advantage is best. }) 16. Nf5 Be2 { [%csl Gd3] } 17. Nxe7+ Qxe7 18. Rfe1 Bxd3 19. Nc5 Bc4! { Avoiding the tempting Bb5, which actually just improves white's queen (while preparing a4-b5). } 20. a3? { Simply unnecessary and too slow. } 20... Ng4! 21. Bd4 Qh4 { [%csl Gf2,Gh2] } 22. Bxe5 (22. h3 exd4 23. hxg4 dxc3 $16) 22... Qxf2+ 23. Kh1 { Objectively speaking, there had to be a win here. In game, I spent a while here and truly couldn't see it. } 23... h5? (23... Ne3! 24. Rg1 Bf1 25. Raxf1 Nxf1 $18 26. Qd1 Ne3 27. Qf3 Qxf3 28. gxf3 Nf5) (23... Re8 24. Qxc6) (23... Bb5 24. Qd1) 24. Bg3 Qb2 25. Rac1 Ne3!! { Necessary! Otherwise, Rc2 traps black's queen. } 26. Rg1 d4! { [%cal Gc4d5,Gd5g2] } 27. Bf4 { Both sides must play with vigor! } 27... Ng4 { [%cal Gg4f2] } 28. Bg3 d3! { Once again preventing Rc2, and creating a monster passed pawn. } { [%csl Gc2] } (28... Bd5?? 29. Rc2 $18) 29. Qd1 Rd8 (29... Ne3 30. Qf3 (30. Qxh5?? Bd5) 30... d2! { The move I had missed. c3 now falls, and black defends his bishop. } 31. Rb1 Qxc3) 30. Ne4 { I thought here for a long time, and came to the conclusion that there is no breakthrough. White's pieces have come back to the defense and black's activity is about to run out. I felt that this conclusion must be wrong in the game, and so kept trying to play with vigor even when there's no more reason to be able to do so. } 30... f5?! (30... Ne3 31. Qd2 Qxd2 32. Nxd2 { I didn't want to allow white the tempo. }) (30... Re8) 31. Qd2 Qxa3?! (31... Qxd2 32. Nxd2 { I didn't want to give white the tempo, when I had been playing so energetically for many moves in a row. } 32... Bf7 33. Rgf1) 32. Nd6!! { White refuses to win the queen, instead getting some activity for his pieces instead! } (32. Ra1 Qxa1!! 33. Rxa1 fxe4 { The point of 30...f5. I was still trying to "play for tricks" going for this unnecessary queen sacrifice instead of just playing solid chess. } 34. Bf4) 32... Rxd6 33. Bxd6 Qa4?? { Black must avoid losing his queen, but this move is much too passive. } (33... Qa2 34. Qxa2 Bxa2 { Objectively best. Black's attack has run out, but has 2 pawns for the exchange (and a monster passed pawn on d3). I still felt that there was more during the game. } 35. Bc5 Bc4 36. Bd4 Re8 37. h3 Ne3 38. Rce1 f4 39. g3 Bd5+ 40. Kh2 d2 { A beautiful line where black takes advantage of white's misplaced pieces even in the endgame. }) 34. Rcf1 Qc2 { Already, black is shown to be on the back foot. } 35. Qf4 Bd5? (35... Be6 36. h3 Nf6 37. Be5 Ne4 { Black keeps all the material, but now the weaknesses around his king become more relevant than white's king safety. }) 36. h3! (36. Qxf5?? Ne3 { This was the tactical justification for move 35, but white finds a stronger reply. }) 36... Nf6 37. Qxf5 Re8 38. Be5 { White asks black "who is attacking whom?" } 38... Ne4 39. Qxh5 Rxe5 { A desperate attempt to reach an endgame where black is only slightly worse. } 40. Qxe5 Nf2+ 41. Kh2! { White refuses to give up any material. } (41. Rxf2 Qxf2 { White already has a perpetual check if they want it, but they might try and play for more being up the exchange. }) 41... d2! { The only move that doesn't roll over immediately. } 42. Qd4 { Not best, but still should be enough to win. } (42. Rxf2 d1=Q 43. Rxd1 Qxf2 { This is clearly losing for black, but at least we reach an endgame where perpetual checks are possible. }) (42. c4!! Bxc4 43. Rxf2 d1=Q 44. Rxd1 Qxd1 45. Qe8+ Kh7 46. Qe4+ Kh6 47. Qxc4 { The point of the ruthless 42. c4. White destabilizes black's pieces in order to mop them up once the dust clears. }) 42... d1=Q 43. Rxd1 Nxd1 44. Qxd1 (44. Rxd1?? Qxg2#) 44... Qxc3 { We've reached an endgame where black is attempting to prove that the monster bishop is worth a rook. Objectively, it's not. } 45. Qa4?? (45. Qg4 Qe5+ 46. Qg3 { The queen on g3 defends the king perfectly Now the rook can get into the game and prove itself better than the bishop. }) 45... Qe5+ 46. Kh1 Qg3 { White resigned. The threat of Qh3# can only be stopped by playing Qb3 or Qa3 and losing a queen completely for free. } *


