1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Bg5 d5 4. Nc3 Be7 5. Nf3 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. a3 { [%cal Ga7a6] } (7. e3 { The mainline }) 7... a6 8. e3 dxc4 9. Bxc4 { Develops his bishop in one move, but allows for the freeing b5-Bb7 maneuver, reminiscent of a Semi-slav. } 9... b5 10. Bb3?! { Blocking the b pawn, so black will be assured to get in the thematic c5 break. } 10... Bb7 11. O-O Nbd7 12. Re1 c5 13. dxc5 Nxc5 14. Qxd8 Rfxd8 15. Bc2 Rac8 16. Rad1 { Black's pieces are optimized, but making progress isn't so simple. } 16... g5 (16... Ncd7!? { Rerouting the knight to the c4 square is an interesting idea that keeps all the tension in the position and ensures my king will remain safe. } { [%cal Gd7b6,Gb6c4] }) 17. Nxg5? (17. Bg3 Nd5 { My plan for the position. Trades a few pieces, but my remaining pieces are optimally placed. } 18. Nxd5 Bxd5) 17... hxg5 18. Bxg5 Kg7 19. e4 Ng8 (19... e5 { I didn't want to give up the d5 square, but locking down the position and ensuring my king is safe along one color complex is the most precise way forward. }) 20. Bf4 f6 { [%cal Ge6e5] } 21. Re3?! Rxd1+ 22. Bxd1 e5 23. Rg3+ Kf7!? 24. Bh5+ { I allowed this check, but ultimately I was much more concerned about a possible bishop check along the a2-g8 diagonal than along the h5-e8 diagonal. Now my king is safe, and my extra piece determines the outcome of the game. } (24. Be3! Rd8 (24... Ne6 25. Bb3 { [%cal Gc8c3] }) 25. Bxc5) 24... Kf8 25. Be3 Nxe4 26. Nxe4 Bxe4 27. Bg4 f5 28. Bh3 (28. Bxf5! Bxf5 29. Rf3 Kf7 30. Rxf5+ Ke6 { A much better line than the game. White remains down the 2 pawns for a piece. }) 28... Rd8! { [%cal Gf5f4] } 29. f4 { The only move, but insufficient due to the following forcing sequence. } 29... Rd1+ 30. Kf2 Bh4 31. Ke2 { Multiple moves win, but I wanted the one that ensured the rooks would be traded. } 31... Bxg3 32. Bc5+ Kf7 33. Kxd1 Bxf4 34. g3 Bg5 35. Bf1 Bd5 36. Kc2 (36. a4?? Bb3+ 37. Ke1 Bxa4) 36... Ne7 { Finally my knight returns to the action. As long as I can keep on a pawn or two, the win should be easy. } 37. b3 Nc6 38. a4 bxa4 39. bxa4 Be7!! { Nice defense! a5 can be supported next. } 40. Bxe7 Kxe7 41. Kd3 a5 (41... Bb3? { Rushing to win the pawn ensures that the pawns will actually be traded off. } 42. Kc3 Bxa4 43. Bxa6) 42. h3 Nd4 43. Kc3 Bc6 44. Kc4 Kd6! { No king activity for you! } 45. g4 Bxa4 46. g5 Bb5+ 47. Kc3 Bxf1 48. g6 Ke6 49. h4 Be2 50. Kd2 Bh5 51. Kd3 Bxg6 52. Ke3 $19 { Black can easily mop up the rest. } *


