1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 Nbd7 4. Nf3 e5 5. Bc4 Be7 6. O-O c6 7. a4 a5 8. Re1 { My preferred setup against the Black Lion. } 8... Qc7 9. Qe2 h6 10. Bb3 (10. Be3 Ng4 11. Bd2!?) 10... Nf8 11. d5!? { I've made as many waiting moves as I can make without play h3 to secure Be3. So I decide to commit with the closing of the center as a way to activate my remaining pieces without touching my kingside. } (11. h3?! g5 { Unless there's an extremely strong reply to g5, I don't want to invite the attack with h3. }) 11... Ng6 12. h3 { Only now that g5 is not coming am I happy to play h3. } 12... Nh5? 13. Be3? { These mutual mistakes will be the theme of this middlegame. Black plays just a slightly bit unsoundly, and I don't see the correct continuation to punish it. } (13. dxc6! bxc6 (13... Nhf4 14. Qc4 Be6 15. cxb7 Qxb7 16. Qb5+) 14. Nxe5 { [%cal Ge2h5] } 14... Nhf4 15. Bxf7+ Kf8 (15... Kd8 16. Bxf4 Nxf4 17. Qd1!) 16. Nxg6+ Kxf7) 13... Nhf4 14. Qc4 c5?? 15. Nb5 (15. Bxf4 Nxf4 16. Nxe5! dxe5 17. d6 Bxd6 18. Nb5 Qe7 19. Nxd6+ Qxd6 20. Qxf7+ Kd8 21. Rad1 Ne2+ 22. Kf1 Nd4 23. Qxg7 Rf8 24. c3 Bd7 25. cxd4 cxd4 { An extremely complicated line that ultimately only wins a pawn (and misplaces the black king). }) 15... Qb8 16. Rad1 (16. Bxf4 Nxf4 17. Nxe5 dxe5 18. d6 Be6 19. Qxc5! { Maintains the pawn and ensures that white will regain the piece or win the exchange with Nc7+. } 19... Bf6 20. Nc7+ Kf8 21. Nxa8 Qxa8 22. d7+ Kg8 23. Bxe6 Nxe6 24. Qb6 $14) 16... Ra6?? { Designed to stop Bxc5 threats, but unleashes other threats instead. } (16... O-O { A much safer and easily understandable move. } 17. Qc3 { The line would essentially to transpose to the game, except black is two tempi ahead. }) 17. Qc3?? (17. Bxf4! Nxf4 18. Nxe5 dxe5 19. d6 Be6 20. Nc7+! Kd7 $18 (20... Qxc7 21. dxc7! { [%cal Ge6c4,Gc7c8] })) 17... O-O 18. Bc4 Ra8 { Black appropriately drops the rook back home to a safer square. } 19. Na3!? { The positional idea is to swap off light squared bishops so that white's only bad piece is exchanged for the potential attacking piece on c8. However, avoiding all trades is slightly better because the space advantage is suffocating black as-is. } 19... Bd7 (19... f5! { Open up the position while white's piece are on the backfoot! }) 20. Bb5 Qc8 21. Bxd7 Qxd7 22. Qb3 (22. Nc4 { The move I wanted to play. But I was worried that black would sacrifice the exchange. } 22... Qxa4 23. Bxf4 Nxf4 24. Nb6 Qb4 25. Nxa8 Rxa8 { This position was unclear to me during the game. I misunderstimated how easily I could now kick black's knight off of the f4 square with g3. }) 22... Ra6? { Black again puts the rook on a square that doesn't contribute to the game. } 23. Nc4 Rb8 24. Qb5 { White wants to trade pieces, misplace black's rook again, and then take the a file to apply pressure to the a pawn. } 24... Nxh3+! { This came as a shock to me during the game. } (24... Qxb5 25. axb5 Ra7 26. Ra1 b6 27. b3 Rd7 { White is better, but it will require coordinating his knights on a4 and c4 to hit the b6 and d6 pawns. }) 25. gxh3 Qxh3 26. Ncd2! { Thankfully I found the only move that defends everything. } { [%cal Gb5f1] } 26... Ra7 (26... Qg4+? 27. Kf1 { This is no problem as white is happy to get his king towards the closed queenside and then use the open g and h files to attack black. }) 27. Qf1 Qg4+ (27... Qd7 28. b3 b5 { I was initially worried about this line, but SF finds a great path forwards. } 29. Ra1 bxa4 30. Rxa4 Rb4 31. Rea1) 28. Qg2 Qh5 29. c4 { Killing all queenside play. Now white's extra piece is enough to win. } 29... b6 30. Nb1 (30. Nf1 { After I played Nb1, I realized that Nf1 was a more forcing alternative. } 30... Rf8 31. Ng3) 30... Bf8 31. Nc3 f6 32. Nh2?! { A step in the wrong direction. I miscalculate the line and thought I was just forcing a queen trade in order to enter a trivially won endgame. } (32. Kf1 Rf7 33. Ke2 { Now white can attack black. }) 32... Nh4 33. Qg4?? Qxg4+ 34. Nxg4 Nf3+ 35. Kg2 Nxe1+ 36. Rxe1 Rf7 37. Bc1 f5 38. exf5 Rxf5 39. Ne4 Rb7 40. Rg1 Kh7 (40... Be7?? 41. Bxh6!) 41. Kf1 Rbf7 42. Be3 Rf3 43. Ke2 g5?? { Finally black cracks. There were many ways to go wrong with my knights so close to black's king, but ultimately black fell for an easy one. } (43... Rh3 44. Bxh6!! Rxh6 (44... gxh6?? 45. Ngf6+ Rxf6 46. Nxf6+ Kh8 47. Rg8#) 45. Ng5+ Kg6 46. Nxf7 Kxf7 47. Nxh6+ gxh6 $18 { I only committed my king towards e2 once I was sure that Rh3 wasn't working. }) (43... Be7 { The move I expected. I was unsure how to make progress at this point, and indeed the computer figures out after a while that it is drawn. }) 44. Bxg5 Rb3 45. Bc1 { Serious threats are now unstoppable once black's rooks are no longer doubled on the f file. } 45... Rb4 (45... Rg7 { The only move to hold it together, but this is obviously terrible. } 46. Nef6+ Kg6) 46. Ngf6+ Rxf6 47. Nxf6+ Kh8 48. Rg8# *


