1. b4 e5 2. Bb2 Bxb4 3. Bxe5 Nf6 4. a3 Be7 5. e3 Nc6 6. Nf3? { Giving up the bishop pair is weak. } 6... Nxe5 7. Nxe5 d6?! { The knight isn't well-placed in the center. Better to simply play d5 and go for a Petrov-like setup. } 8. Nf3 O-O 9. d4 b6 10. c4 Bb7 11. Be2 c5 12. Nc3 (12. d5 b5! { The idea if white tries to build a strong center. Black is timely in breaking it down in a benko-like manner }) 12... d5!! { Open up the center while white's king is in the center. d5 also allows the bishop pair to dominate the board! } 13. O-O cxd4 14. Nxd4 dxc4 15. Bxc4 Rc8 { Juicy targets on the c file. } { [%csl Gc4,Gc3] } 16. Qd3 Qc7 17. Ne6?! { An interesting try, but I calculated the line where black wins. } (17. Nf5!? { The only move I thought white had to hold it all together. } 17... Rfd8 (17... Ng4! 18. Nxe7+ Qxe7 19. Bd5 Rxc3 20. Qxc3 Bxd5 21. Qd4 Nf6 $19) 18. Nxe7+ Qxe7 19. Qe2 b5 20. Nxb5 Qe4 $19 { [%cal Ge4g2,Ge4c4] }) 17... Qxc4 18. Qxc4 Rxc4 19. Nxf8 Rxc3! { The white knight on f8 is trapped! } 20. Rac1 Rxc1 21. Rxc1 Kxf8 22. Rc7 Bd5 23. Rxa7 Bc5 24. Rc7 Bxa3 { White resigned. } *


