1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. c4 d6 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bg4 6. Be2 O-O 7. Be3 c5 8. d5 Nbd7 9. Nd2 Bxe2 10. Qxe2 Qb6 11. Rb1! { It's important not to touch the queenside pawns or reposition the knight on d2 in case of the e6 strike. } 11... Ne5 12. h3 a5 13. f4 Ned7 (13... Nh5!? 14. fxe5 Ng3 15. Qf3 Nxh1 16. g4 Bxe5 17. Qxh1 $16 { [%cal Gd2b1,Ge5c3] }) 14. O-O e5 (14... e6 15. Qd3 exd5 16. cxd5 { Transitioning to a benoni structure makes more sense here. }) 15. f5 Qd8 16. Rf2 Nb8 17. Rbf1 h6 18. fxg6 fxg6 19. Nb5 Na6 20. a3 g5 21. Rf5 Nc7 22. Nc3 b6 23. R1f2 Ra7 24. Qf3 Nce8 25. Nf1 a4 26. Qd1 Qa8 27. Ng3 Rff7 28. Qf1 Qd8 29. Nb5 Rab7 30. Qd1 Qa8 31. Nc3 Ra7 32. Nf1 Nc7 33. Nh2 Nce8 34. Bc1 Nh7 35. Qh5 Rxf5 36. exf5 Nef6 37. Qe2 Nf8 38. g4 Qe8 39. Nf1 e4! { The only scary move. Given one more move, white can take control of the e4 square and ensure black's bishop remains entombed. } (39... Rd7 40. Ng3 $18 { [%cal Gg3e4,Gc3e4,Ge2e4] }) 40. Ng3 Re7 41. Qe1?? (41. Kg2! e3 (41... N8d7 42. Nb5 { [%cal Gb5d6] } 42... Qb8 $16 { [%cal Gc1d2,Gd2c3,Ge2c2] }) 42. Rf3 $16) 41... e3 42. Re2 N8d7!! 43. Rxe3 Ne5?? (43... Nxd5 44. Nxd5! { [%cal Gd5e3] }) (43... Rxe3 44. Qxe3 Qxe3+ 45. Bxe3 Ne5 46. Nxa4 Nxc4 47. Bc1 Nxd5 $15 { Black takes away the initiative and the center from white in this line. I saw this and was sure I was lost. Thankfully, white can tactically ensure a draw here. } 48. Ne4 b5 49. Nac3 Nxc3 50. bxc3 { [%cal Gd6d5,Ge4c5] }) 44. Qe2 { [%cal Ge2f3,Ge2c4,Ge5f3,Ge5c4] } 44... Kf7 45. Kf2 Ned7 46. Rxe7+ Qxe7 47. Qxe7+ Kxe7 48. Nxa4 Ne5 { Transposing to the scary line I saw earlier, except white is up a crucial tempo here. } { [%cal Ge5d3,Ge5c4,Gd3c1,Gd3f2] } 49. Ke2 Nxc4 50. b3! Na5 51. Nxb6 Nxb3 52. Bb2 { The position has changed to an endgame where the passed a pawn will be very difficult to stop. } 52... Kf7 53. Kd3 Nd4 (53... Nxg4?? 54. Bxg7 Nf2+ 55. Kc3 $18) 54. Bxd4! cxd4 55. a4 Ke8 56. a5 Nd7 (56... Kd8 57. a6 Kc7 58. a7 Kb7 59. a8=Q+ { Justification of white's play. }) 57. Nxd7 Kxd7 58. Ne2 Kc7 59. Nxd4 Bxd4 (59... Kb7 60. Nf3 Ka6 61. Nd2 Kxa5 62. Ne4 Be5 63. f6 Kb6 64. Kc4 Kc7 65. f7 Bg7 66. Ng3 Kd7 67. Nf5 Bf8 68. Kb5 Kc7 69. Nd4 Kb7 70. Ne6 { Not taking the knight still leads to an easy win as white has a really good knight vs a terrible bishop. }) 60. Kxd4 { Black resigned. } *


