1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6 4. O-O Bd7 5. c3 Nf6 6. Re1 Be7 7. d4 exd4 8. cxd4 O-O 9. Nc3 a6 10. Bf1! { Always retreat. I've been in this (and similar positions) several times, and I know that Bf1 gets the pieces out of the way and on the route to better pastures. } 10... Bg4 { [%csl Gd4] } 11. Be3 (11. h3?! Bxf3 12. gxf3 { I would prefer to get this position, but without h3 in. The light squared bishop keeps the king very safe. }) 11... h6? 12. g3? (12. Qb3 Na5 13. Qc2! { Maneuver to c2, but first misplace the knight. }) 12... d5! { Black gets just enough of the center to claim equality. } 13. e5 Ne4 14. Bg2 (14. h3 Bf5 15. Nd2 { A better version than in the game. During the game, I was trying my best to avoid h3, seeing it as a potential target for an eventual queen+bishop battery. }) 14... Bb4 15. Qb3 Bxc3 16. bxc3 b6?? (16... Bxf3? 17. Bxf3 { [%cal Ge4d2] } 17... Nd2?? 18. Bxd2) (16... Na5 { Obviously correct. Black kicks white's queen around with tempo, and repositions to the c4 square. } 17. Qc2 Bf5 18. Nh4 Bh7 19. Qc1!! { In my calculations, I missed this queen retreat, justifying white's play. All of a sudden, black's knight is trapped in the middle of the board! }) 17. Nd2?? { Mutual blunder. I wanted to trade off black's knight instead of seeing that it was trapped. } (17. Nh4! g5?? (17... Na5 18. Qc2 { [%csl Ge4] }) 18. f3 gxh4 19. fxe4 $18 { Black's kingside is in shatters, and white still has the center. }) 17... Bf5 18. Nxe4 Bxe4 19. f3!? { I wanted to keep the bishop pair, but ultimately, that light squared bishop for black turns into a monster. It would have been more direct to trade and target that weak pawn. } (19. Bxe4 dxe4 20. Qc2 { [%cal Gc2e4] } 20... Qd5 21. c4 Qd7 22. Qxe4 $16) 19... Bf5 20. Bf2 Ne7? { Going in the wrong direction. The c4 outpost was crying to be taken control of. } 21. a4 Rb8 22. Bf1 { [%csl Ga6] } 22... Qc8 23. c4?! { I figured it was important to offload my potential weakness, but ultimately this gives black too much play on the queenside, while weakening my center. } (23. Qa3!? Nc6 { [%cal Gc6a5,Ga4a5] } 24. Qa2! { An interesting maneuver that I missed during the game. }) 23... Be6 24. Rac1 (24. c5!? bxc5 25. Qa3 { [%cal Ga3e7] }) 24... c5 25. cxd5 Bxd5 26. Qa3 Qc6 27. Rc3 (27. Bxa6! Bxf3 28. dxc5 bxc5 29. Bf1! $18 { I did not appreciate just how strong this position is. My two bishops rake the queenside, and make blockading the outside passed pawn nearly impossible. }) 27... Rfc8 28. dxc5?? { I saw that crashing through on c5 was going to lead to excellent chances. Is black up to the challenge? } (28. Bxa6 { Obviously best. I missed this move in time pressure. }) 28... b5!! { Brilliant pawn sacrifice. Normally, the queen does not enjoy being the blockader, but here black's passed b pawn ends up being scarier than white's blockaded traitor on c5. } 29. axb5 axb5 { [%cal Gb5b4] } 30. Rcc1? { And white immediately crumbles. } (30. Rd3! b4 31. Qb2 Bxf3 32. e6! { The moves I was most scared of turn out to be innocuous due to white's attacking ideas in the center. }) 30... Bxf3 31. Bh3 { [%csl Gc8] } 31... b4 32. Qd3?? { Completely incorrect. I fell in love with the idea of playing Qd6, "forcing" a trade on d6 and pushing my two connected passed pawns to victory lane. Unfortunately, I had spent my entire time evaluating Qb2 that I missed the obvious rejoinder to this move. } (32. Qb2 { The only move I was seriously considering, but I didn't see how I was making progress in this position and figured I was just simply worse with no real counterplay. }) 32... Rd8 33. Qe3 { White has to admit defeat and can't even retreat to the preferred square of b2. White is now busted. } 33... b3 34. e6 Bd5?? (34... f6 { I was already contemplating resigning in this position. The b pawn is so strong that white will have to sacrifice the exchange. } 35. Rb1 b2 36. Qc3 Qb7 37. Bf1 Be4 { Black looks clearly winning, but white has a stunner: } 38. c6!! Bxc6 (38... Nxc6?? 39. Rxe4 $18) (38... Qxc6 39. Qxc6 Bxc6 40. Re2 $10) 39. Re2 $10 { [%csl Gb2] }) 35. exf7+ { [%csl Ge7] } 35... Kf8?? 36. Qxe7# { Complete collapse from black. Black allowed white to crash through in a completely winning position. } *


