1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d6 5. Bg5 Nbd7 6. Nf3 h6 7. Bh4 O-O 8. e4?! { This move is almost never correct because the e pawn is only defended by the pinned queenside pieces. } 8... e5 (8... Bxc3+!? 9. Qxc3 e5 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Nxe5?? g5) 9. dxe5 dxe5 10. Rd1 Qe7 (10... Bxc3+?! 11. Qxc3 g5 12. Bg3 Nxe4 13. Qe3 f5 { I didn't believe this position. Indeed, the computer finds a way forward for white. } (13... Nxg3?! 14. hxg3 Kg7) 14. c5!! { [%cal Ga2g8] }) 11. Be2 Re8 12. O-O c6 { [%cal Gc3d5,Gc3b5] } (12... Bxc3 13. Qxc3 g5 14. Bg3 Nxe4 15. Qc2 { Finally it makes sense to go for this pawn. But I didn't like how my bishop was still blocked in, whereas white was fully developed, so I opted for more calm play. }) 13. a3 Ba5?! 14. b4 Bc7 15. b5?? (15. Rfe1 Nf8 16. c5 Ng6 17. Bg3 Be6 { My expectations. }) 15... Nf8 (15... Qxa3!?) 16. bxc6 bxc6 17. a4 Ng6 18. Bg3 Nh5 19. Rd2 (19. Nxe5?? Nxg3 20. Nxg6 { [%cal Gg6e7] } 20... Nxe2+ 21. Kh1 fxg6 { The check saves the day. }) 19... Nhf4 (19... Nxg3 20. hxg3 { While this wins the bishop pair, I felt that my knight was better than his bishop. }) 20. Rfd1 Nxe2+ (20... Qc5!? 21. Bf1 Bg4!) 21. Nxe2 Qc5 (21... Rb8 22. h3 Be6 23. Nc3 Qc5 24. Nd5 Ba5! (24... cxd5?? 25. cxd5 Qxc2 26. Rxc2 $14) 25. Nxe5 Bxd2) 22. Nc1!? Be6 23. Nd3 (23. Nd4! Bg4 24. f3?? exd4! { [%cal Gd4d3,Gc5g1] }) 23... Qxc4 24. Qxc4 Bxc4 25. Rc1 Bxd3 (25... Ba5 { I really wanted this move to work, but ultimately I found a refutation. } 26. Rxc4 Bxd2 27. Nxd2 Rad8 28. Rc3 Rd4 29. Nc4 $16) 26. Rxd3 Rad8 27. Rdc3 Re6 { [%cal Gd8d1] } 28. h3 Nf4!? (28... f6 29. Rxc6 Rxc6 30. Rxc6 Rd1+ 31. Kh2 Bb6 { [%csl Gf2] } 32. Rc2 Ra1 { The computer likes just shutting down the bishop and knight here. }) (28... Rdd6!? { This was my initial calculation. But it seemed wrong to put both of my rooks on baby-sitting duty. Instead, I decided to sacrifice the pawn back for initiative. }) 29. Bxf4 exf4 30. Rxc6 Rxc6 31. Rxc6 Rd1+ 32. Kh2 Bb6 33. g3 fxg3+ 34. Kxg3 Rf1?? { While it looks strong, there's a refutation that unfortunately directly leads to a perpetual check. } (34... Ra1 35. Rc4 Ra3 36. Kg2 Ra2! { Transitions to a better version than the game. }) 35. Rc8+ Kh7 36. Ne5! Rxf2 { [%cal Gf2f7] } (36... Bxf2+?? 37. Kg2 $18) 37. Nd7 { [%cal Gd7b6,Gg3f2] } (37. a5?! Bd4 38. Nf3 (38. Nc6 Be3 (38... Rd2 39. Rd8 Be5+! { [%cal Gd2d8] } 40. Kf3 Rxd8 41. Nxd8 Bc7 42. Nxf7?? (42. Nc6 a6 $17) 42... Kg8! $19 { [%csl Gd6,Ge5,Gd8] } (42... Bxa5 43. e5 Kg6 44. Nd6 { I was trying to analyze this position, and I was sure it was winning, but I missed one key idea. } 44... Bb4! (44... Bc7?? 45. Nb5! Bb8 46. Ke4 Kf7 47. Kd5 a5 48. e6+ Kf6 { It should still be winning. })))) 38... Be3 39. Rc3 Re2!) 37... Rd2 38. Nf8+ $10 { Perpetual is unavoidable } 38... Kg8 39. Ne6+ { And white holds the draw. } { [%cal Ge6d8,Gd2d8,Gb6d8] } *


