1. e4 e5 { [%csl Ge4,Ge5] } 2. g3 { [%cal Gf1g2] } 2... Nf6 { [%csl Ge4] } 3. Bg2 Bc5 { [%csl Gf2][%cal Gc5d4] } 4. h3 { [%cal Gf6g4,Gc5f2,Gg4f2] } 4... d6?! { Unnecessary unless the e pawn is actually attacked. In this game, indeed I could break with d5 in one move. } 5. Ne2 O-O 6. O-O Be6 7. d3 Qd7 { [%csl Gh3] } 8. Kh2 Nc6 9. Nbc3 d5! { [%cal Gd5d4] } (9... h6? { Too slow. Black needs to strike in the center immediately. } 10. f4!) 10. Bg5!? (10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Ne4 Bb6 { This position is very similar to a Pirc-type position that I get, but with colors reversed. }) 10... d4 11. Na4 Be7 { [%csl Ge7][%cal Ge7f6] } 12. c3?? b5! { [%csl Ga4] } 13. cxd4 bxa4?? (13... exd4 14. e5!? Nxe5 15. Bxa8 (15. Bxf6 gxf6 { [%cal Ge7c5] } 16. Bxa8 Rxa8 $19 { [%csl Ga4] }) 15... Rxa8 { I miscalculated this line, not realizing that the knight on a4 is still trapped. }) 14. d5 { [%csl Ge6,Gc6] } 14... Bxd5 (14... Nxd5 15. exd5 Bxd5 16. Bxd5 Qxd5 17. Bxe7 Nxe7 { A much better version than in the game. In the game, it's clear that white's bishop is stronger than black's knight. }) 15. exd5 Nxd5 16. Bxe7 Ncxe7 17. Nc3 a3!? (17... Nxc3!? 18. bxc3 Rad8 19. Qe2 Ng6 { [%cal Gg6e5] } 20. Rad1 { Also an interesting try for black to win. }) 18. Qb3 (18. Nxd5!? Nxd5 19. bxa3 { With c6 coming soon to cement my knight on its central outpost, I was sure this was better for black. }) 18... axb2 19. Qxb2 Rab8 20. Qa3 Nxc3 21. Qxc3 Rfd8 (21... Qd6!? { The queen is slightly less active here, but serves a strong defensive duty holding the dark squares together. } 22. Rfe1 f6 23. Rac1 c6 24. Bxc6?? Rfc8 { [%cal Gc8c1] }) 22. Qa5?! { This move allows me to reconfigure my pieces defensively. } { [%cal Ga5a7,Ga5e5,Ga5c7] } (22. Qxe5 Rb5 23. Qc3 Nd5 { My expectations. }) 22... Nc6 { [%cal Gc6e5,Gc6a7,Gc6a5] } 23. Bxc6?! { Now black's terrible knight is traded for white's great bishop. } (23. Qa4!? Nd4! 24. Qxa7 Qd6 { Tending towards a draw, as a lot of pawns are being traded off. }) 23... Qxc6 24. Qxe5 Rxd3 25. Rac1 { [%cal Ge5c7,Gc1c7] } 25... Qd6 { [%cal Gc7d6] } 26. Qa5? (26. Qxd6 cxd6 27. Rc7 Ra3 28. Rb1!! (28. Re1 { [%cal Ge1e7] } 28... Rxa2 29. Ree7 Rxf2+ $19 { [%cal Gf2f7] }) 28... Rf8 29. Rbb7 Rxa2 30. Kg2 g6 $10 { The activity of white's rooks make up for the one pawn deficit white sill soon be in. }) 26... Rxg3! 27. Qxc7 (27. fxg3?? Rb2+ { [%csl Gc2,Gd2,Gf2] } 28. Kh1 Qxg3 $19 { [%cal Gg3h2,Gg3h3,Gg3g2] }) 27... Qxc7 28. Rxc7 Ra3 { [%csl Gc7][%cal Gc7f7,Gc7a7] } 29. Rfc1? (29. Rb1! Rf8 30. Rbb7 Rxa2 31. Kg3 a5 { White is still probably drawing this because of the passivity of one of black's rooks. }) 29... g6 { [%cal Gg8g7] } 30. R1c2?! { The wrong idea. White is now the passive one, by choice. } { [%cal Gc2f2,Gc2a2] } 30... Rb6 { Afterwards, I should have played Rb5-f5 immediately instead. } { [%cal Gb6f6,Gf6f2,Gf6f7,Ga3a2,Ga3a7] } 31. f4 Rf6 32. Rf2 { [%cal Gf4f5] } 32... Rf5 { Never trade pawns. } { [%cal Gf5f7,Gf5f4,Ga3a2,Ga3a7] } 33. Kg2 Kg7 34. Rb7!? h6 { [%cal Gg6g5] } 35. Rb4 (35. Rb3 Ra4 36. Kg3 { I thought the idea of Rb7 was to get white's king more active, such as in this line. However, white's actual idea was just to wait... a clear mistake. }) 35... g5 { [%csl Ga2][%cal Gf4g5,Gf5f2,Gg2f2,Ga3a2,Gh6g5] } (35... Rfa5 36. f5 Rxf5 37. Rxf5 gxf5 38. Rb2 { The computer sees this as easily winning. I had my doubts however. }) 36. Kf1 (36. fxg5 Rxf2+ 37. Kxf2 Rxa2+ 38. Kg3 hxg5 { I was sure that I could still win in this position even though we traded pawns because of the passed a pawn AND the kingside majority. } 39. h4 gxh4+ 40. Kxh4 { [%csl Gf7,Ga2][%cal Gh4g3,Gg3f2,Gf1f7] }) 36... Rxh3 37. Ra4 { Finally, white gets the memo about activity. But now, black has two connected passed pawns on the kingside that become the sole focus of the game. } 37... g4! { Never trade pawns, even if it's losing a pawn! } { [%csl Gg4,Gh6][%cal Gg4g1,Gh6h1,Ga2a7] } 38. Kg2 (38. Rxa7 h5 39. Ra4 Rc3 40. Kg2 h4 41. Rf1 h3+ 42. Kh2 Rc2+ 43. Kh1 (43. Kg3 Rg2+ 44. Kh4 Kg6 $19 { [%cal Gf5h5] }) 43... g3 44. Re1 Rh2+ 45. Kg1 Rg2+ 46. Kh1 Rc5 47. f5 Rcc2 48. f6+ Kg6 49. Rg4+ Kf5 50. Rge4 Rh2+ 51. Kg1 Rcg2+ 52. Kf1 Rh1# { One possible continuation, highlighting how fast black's pawns are. }) 38... a5 39. Re2 { A good try. White again strives for activity. } { [%cal Ge2e5] } 39... h5 (39... f6!? 40. Re7+ Kg6 41. Ra7 h5 42. R7xa5 { I was sure I was better here, but I didn't want to play f6, unless I absolutely had to. It's never smart to weaken the king. }) 40. Re5 Kg6 41. Rexa5 (41. Raxa5 Rxe5 42. fxe5 { [%cal Gh5h4,Gg4g3] }) 41... h4 42. Ra6+ f6 43. Re4 Rf3! { [%cal Gf3f4] } 44. Raa4 h3+ 45. Kg1 g3 46. Re1 R3xf4 { Inaccurate. Black can easily win in the alternative line. } (46... Rf2 47. Ra8 (47. Rc4 h2+ 48. Kh1 Rh5 $19 { [%cal Gg3g2] }) 47... Rg2+ 48. Kh1 Rxf4 49. Rg8+ Kf5 50. Rb1 Rff2 51. Rb5+ Ke6 52. Rb6+ Kd7 53. Rb7+ Kc6 54. Rb1 Rh2+ 55. Kg1 Rfg2+ 56. Kf1 Rh1#) 47. Rxf4 Rxf4 { [%csl Gh3,Gg3] } 48. Re3! Rg4 { Now black's job becomes a lot harder. Instead, his king should be on g4, and his rook should be on f4. } 49. a4 { [%cal Gg4a4,Ge3g3,Gg6f5,Gg3h3] } 49... Kf5 50. a5 Kf4 51. Rc3 (51. Ra3 Rg8 52. a6 f5 53. a7 Rc8 54. Ra1 Ra8 55. Ra6 Kg4 56. Kh1 f4 $19 { [%cal Gf4f3,Gf3f2,Gf2f1] }) 51... Rg5 { [%csl Gf2] } 52. Ra3 Re5 53. Ra1 { [%cal Ge5e1] } (53. Ra4+ Kf3 54. Ra3+ Re3 55. Rxe3+ Kxe3 56. a6 h2+ 57. Kg2 h1=Q+ 58. Kxh1 Kf2 59. a7 g2+ 60. Kh2 g1=Q+ 61. Kh3 Qg3# { A common, king and pawn endgame trick saves the day! }) 53... Kg4 54. a6 (54. Ra4+ Kf3 55. Ra3+ Re3 { Transitioning to the aformentioned trick. }) 54... h2+ 55. Kg2 Re2+ { [%csl Gf1,Gh1] } 56. Kh1 (56. Kf1 Rf2+ 57. Ke1 h1=R#) 56... Kh3 { [%cal Gg3g2] } 57. Rg1 (57. a7 g2#) (57. Ra3 { [%cal Ga3h3,Ga6a7,Ga7a8] } 57... Re1#) 57... g2+ 58. Rxg2 Re1+ 59. Rg1 Rxg1# *


