1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 5. Ng3 Bg6 6. h4 h6 7. h5 Bh7 8. Nf3 Nd7 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 e6 11. Bf4 Bb4+ 12. c3 Be7 13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. Bxe5 Nf6 15. Ne4 O-O 16. f3 Nxe4 17. Qxe4 Bf6 18. g4 Bxe5 19. dxe5 { [%csl Gd5,Ga5,Gb6][%cal Gd8a5,Ga5b6,Ga5d5] } 19... Qd5 (19... Qa5 20. f4 Rfd8 21. Qe2) 20. Qe2 Rfd8 21. Rd1 { [%csl Ga2][%cal Gd5a2] } 21... Qa5?? { Did I seriously miss the hanging a2 pawn? } 22. f4 Rxd1+ 23. Qxd1 Rd8 24. Qb1 Qc5 (24... Qd5 25. O-O { I didn't want to allow white to castle, but here it is not a good move because of the following sequence. } 25... Qc5+ 26. Rf2 (26. Kh1 Qe3 { [%cal Ge3f4,Ge3h3,Gd8d2] }) 26... Rd2 27. Qf1 Rxb2) 25. Qe4 Qb5 { [%csl Gb2] } 26. Rh2 Qd5?? (26... Rd5 27. g5 hxg5 28. h6 gxf4!) 27. Qxd5 Rxd5 28. Rd2 Kf8 29. Ke2 Ke7 (29... Rxd2+ 30. Kxd2 g6 $10 { This timely break should be enough to prevent any kingside breakthroughs as in the game. The draw is simple because the queenside pawns are symmetric. }) 30. Rxd5 cxd5 { Now that the queenside pawns have been forced up, there is an entrance path that the white king now has that must be tended to with b6. Sadly, this b6 pawn can't be relied upon... } 31. Kd3 Kd7 32. Kd4 b6 33. a4 a6 (33... Kc7 34. c4 dxc4 35. Kxc4 Kc6 36. f5 Kb7 37. f6 { The kingside breakthrough now that can't be stopped because of the threat of the queenside infiltration. } 37... gxf6 38. exf6 $18 { [%cal Gg4g5,Gh6g5,Gh5h6] }) 34. a5 Kc6 35. axb6 Kxb6 36. f5! { Now that my king has been sent to the queenside, there is a decisive breakthrough on the kingside. } 36... Kc6 37. f6! gxf6 38. exf6 Kd6 39. g5! { The final breakthrough. } 39... e5+ 40. Kd3 Ke6 41. gxh6 Kxf6 { A very nice position. Black's king cannot approach the h pawns. In combination with the traitor pawn on f7, black's king is immobile. White wins simply by running black out of moves everywhere else on the board. } 42. b3 a5 43. c4 e4+ 44. Kc3 dxc4 45. Kxc4 (45. bxc4 a4 46. c5 a3 47. c6 a2 48. Kb2 e3 49. h7 (49. c7 e2) 49... Kg7 50. h8=Q+! Kxh8 51. c7 e2 52. c8=Q+) *


