1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 5. Ng3 Bg6 6. h4 h6 7. h5 Bh7 8. Bd3 Bxd3 (8... Qxd4!? { I didn't even see this, but ultimately it transpose to a line I don't like for black so much. }) 9. Qxd3 Nf6 10. Nf3 e6 11. Bf4 Qa5+ 12. Bd2 Qc7 (12... Qa6!? { [%cal Gd3a6,Gb8a6] } 13. Ne5 Bd6 $10) 13. O-O-O Nbd7 14. Ne5?! { An interesting pawn sacrifice, but ultimately not one that should give white anything. While Be7 here should also be fine, I decided to ask my opponent to prove the compensation. } 14... Nxe5 15. dxe5 Qxe5 16. Bc3 (16. Rhe1!?) 16... Qd5! 17. Bxf6 Qxd3 18. Rxd3 gxf6 19. Rhd1 { With the infiltration on the d file coming, precise play is important here. } 19... Be7 20. Ne4 (20. Rd7 Rb8 21. Rc7 { [%cal Gd1d7] } 21... Bd8! $19) 20... f5?! (20... Rd8? { My original idea falls flat. } 21. Rxd8+ Bxd8 22. Nd6+ $10) (20... Rg8! { The move required! The counterattack on g2 gives black the extra tempo he needs to sort his position out. } 21. g3 Rb8 22. Rd7? (22. Nd6+ Kf8 $17) 22... f5! $19 { [%cal Ge8d7,Ge4d6] }) 21. Nd6+ Bxd6 22. Rxd6 O-O 23. Rd7 Rab8 24. Re7 Rfe8 25. Rdd7? (25. Rc7!? { I would have no better than a draw here because the infiltration on the seventh rank is fatal. } { [%cal Ge8c8,Gc7e7,Gc8e8,Ge7c7] }) 25... Rxe7 26. Rxe7 Kg7 27. Kd2 Kf6 28. Rd7 a5 29. Kc3 b5 { Black has untangled by moving the cluttered seventh. At this point, the only issue is king position. } 30. Kd4 c5+!? (30... Rg8! 31. g3 Rg4+ 32. Ke3 (32. Kc5?? Rc4+ $19) 32... Rc4 { With a clearly winning endgame - more active rook, up a pawn, and equal king positions. }) 31. Kxc5? { The natural response, but a blunder. } (31. Ke3! { I didn't see this in the game, but apparently this is enough for white to still play on. }) 31... Rc8+ 32. Kxb5 Rxc2 33. Kxa5 Rxb2 34. a4 Rxf2 { When the dust settles, black retains his extra pawn, but white's passed a pawn is scarier than black's passed e pawn, so the position is still somewhat unclear to the human eye. } 35. Kb5 (35. g3! Rf3 36. Kb4 Rxg3 37. a5 { A slight improvement over the game. } { [%cal Gb4a3,Gg3a3] } 37... f4 (37... Rg1 38. Rd3 { [%cal Gd3a3] } 38... Ra1 39. Ra3 Rxa3 40. Kxa3 f4 $19 { Yet this is still winning for black. }) 38. a6 Rg1 39. a7 Ra1 $19) 35... Rxg2 36. a5 f4 (36... Rb2+ 37. Kc6 Ra2 38. Kb6 { I didn't see how this was an improvement for black, but SF says this is completely over? }) 37. a6 f3 38. Rd1 Ra2 { [%cal Ga2a8] } 39. Kb6 e5! { Black is preparing to sacrifice his rook for the a pawn, and win with his connected passers on the e and f files. } 40. a7 e4 41. Kb7 f2! 42. a8=Q (42. Rd6+ Ke5 43. Ra6 Rxa6 44. Kxa6 f1=Q+ $19 { The usual trick fails because the f pawn is too far advanced. }) 42... Rxa8 43. Kxa8 e3 44. Rd6+ Kg5 45. Rd5+ Kg4 46. Rd4+ Kxh5 47. Rf4 e2 48. Rxf2 e1=Q { White resigned rather than play out this clearly winning position. Note that even the f pawn is immune from capture due to Qe8+ and a fork. } *


