1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 d6 7. c3 O-O 8. h3 Nd7 9. d4 exd4 10. cxd4 f5 11. exf5 Rxf5 12. Bc2 Rf8 13. Nc3 (13. Qd3 Nf6 14. a3 { In retrospect, this is a far superior move order for white. }) 13... Nb4 14. Bb3+ Kh8 15. a3 Nc6 16. Qd3?! { Lining myself up for the unfortunate following idea: } 16... Nb6! 17. Bc2?? (17. g4! { It's absolutely necessary to stop Bf5, dislodging by queen }) 17... Bf5! { Obvious, but good. I completely missed that Nb6 threatened Bf5 here, and now I'm worse. I only expected g6, in which case I would be doing well after Bh6. } 18. Qxf5!? { I decide the most interesting line is to sacrifice my queen as the normal moves should be losing after: } (18. Qd1 Bxc2 19. Qxc2 Rxf3! 20. gxf3 Nxd4 $15) 18... Rxf5 19. Bxf5 Bf6! { It's important to target my d4 weakness before I can play Bf4 followed by Rad1 - with a harmonious piece setup. } (19... Kg8? 20. Be3 { [%cal Gb6c4,Gf5e6] } 20... Bf6 21. Rad1 $15) 20. d5 Na5 (20... Bxc3!? 21. bxc3 Nxd5 22. Be6 Nf6 { I thought black was much better here, but I missed an important line here: } 23. Ng5! { And white will have a draw by forced repetition } { [%cal Gg5f7] }) 21. Bf4?? (21. Ne4! Nxd5 { I thought this move directly refuted Ne4, but I missed: } 22. Be6! c6 23. Neg5 $10 { [%cal Gg5f7] }) 21... Nac4 22. Be6 (22. Ne4?! Nxd5 23. Be6?? Nxf4 { Now this line is refuted }) 22... Nxb2 23. Ne4! Nd3 24. Nxf6 { I thought this move was forced in order to maintain the bishop pair and keep the initiative by sacrificing the exchange. Amazingly, black has even better. } (24. Nfg5!! { [%cal Gg5f7] } 24... Bxg5 25. Nxg5 Qf6 26. Nf7+ Kg8 27. Ne5+ { And white's pieces are so good that black's best bet is to sacrifice the queen. } 27... Qxe6! (27... Kh8 28. Nxd3 $16) 28. dxe6 dxe5 29. Bxe5 Nxe1 30. Rxe1 $14) 24... Qxf6 25. Be3 Nxe1 26. Rxe1 Re8 { I'm down so much material, but my piece coordination is perfect. I'm certainly not equal, but it's incredibly hard to make progress here after: } 27. Bd4 Qf4 28. Rb1 Qe4 29. Re1 Qc2 30. Re3 Qc4?? { A blunder, but a logical one. Black is desperately trying to remove the d5 pawn and e6 bishop construction that he misses the following sequence } { [%cal Gc4d5,Gb6d5] } (30... Nxd5! 31. Bxd5 Rxe3 32. fxe3 c5 { Black can give back material to make immediate progress, and reach a winning endgame }) 31. Rc3! Qa2 (31... c5! 32. Rxc4 Nxc4 33. Ba1 { The engine gives this line and says "equal", but I like white's chances still. }) 32. Rxc7 { [%cal Gc7g7,Gd4h8,Ge6g8,Gf3g5] } 32... Nxd5 33. Bxg7# *


