1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. c4 a6 7. N5c3 Nf6 8. Be2 Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. Be3 Be6 { I've gotten this position several times and I honestly struggle to convert it. If white isn't careful, black will remove all the defenders of d4 and then sink a knight in on that square with a great game. } 11. f3 (11. Na3 { Probably best. However I held out hopes of Nd5 followed by the other knight coming to c3. } 11... Rc8 12. Rc1 h6 13. Qd2 Ng4 14. Bxg4! { Important to remove this knight or white will be worse. } 14... Bxg4 15. Nd5 { Polgar, Judit - Radjabov, Teimour, 1/2-1/2, Baku Presidents Cup, 2010, https://lichess.org/UJT3jYPu }) 11... Nh5 12. Nd5 f5 13. Bb6 (13. Nbc3 fxe4 14. fxe4 Rxf1+ 15. Qxf1 $14 { It is annoying to remaneuver the queen from f1, but black first has to deal with their hanging knight on h5. There is no good option here for black. } 15... Nf6 16. Qf2 { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gd8d7,Gd5b6] }) 13... Qd7 14. Nc7 Rac8 15. Nxe6 Qxe6 16. Nc3 Nf4 17. Nd5 Nxe2+ (17... Nxd5?? 18. cxd5 { [%cal Gd5c6,Gd5e6] }) 18. Qxe2 Nd4 19. Qd3 (19. Bxd4 exd4 20. Rfe1 fxe4 21. Qxe4 Qxe4 22. Rxe4?? Rxc4 { I missed that at the end of this line, the e7 bishop would be hanging... }) 19... fxe4 20. fxe4 (20. Qxe4 Rxc4 21. Kh1! Rfc8 22. b3 { And white will win back the d4 knight+pawn anyway. }) 20... Bg5 (20... Bf6 21. b3 Kh8 { I wasn't completely sure how to make progress here, but I figured I would eventually win the trapped knight on d4 with a timely Nxf6. Engine shows that it works immediately: } 22. Nxf6 Rxf6 23. Rxf6 Qxf6 24. Rf1! { [%cal Gf6d4] } 24... Qe7 25. Bxd4 exd4 26. Qxd4 $16) 21. Bxd4 exd4 22. Qxd4 Bf6 { [%cal Gf6b2] } 23. Nxf6+! { Simplifying the position dramatically, but white is up a clean pawn. } 23... Rxf6 24. Rxf6 Qxf6 25. Qxf6 { I figured this was simpler, but it's always difficult to convert rook endgames... } (25. Qd5+ Qf7 26. b3 { [%cal Gd5d6] } 26... Qxd5 27. exd5 Rf8 28. Rf1! Re8 29. Kf2 { With a clean structure and up a pawn, white should be able to convert this. }) 25... gxf6 26. b3 Kf7 27. Kf2 Ke6 (27... b5!? 28. cxb5 axb5 29. a4! { An important breakthrough so that white's rook is already optimally placed. } (29. Ke3 Rc2 30. a4 { Without this move, white is not winning. })) (27... Rc5 28. a4! { And then white will activate their rook. } { [%cal Gb7b5] } 28... Rh5 29. h3 Rg5 30. Rd1 Ke6 31. Rd5 $18) 28. Ke3 Ke5? { Pressure on e4 is a pipe dream, and this merely allows white a crucial tempo down the line. } (28... f5! 29. exf5+ Kxf5 30. Rf1+ Ke6 31. g4 Rg8 32. Rf4 $18 h5?? (32... b5 33. h4 bxc4 34. Rxc4 $18) 33. gxh5 Rg2 34. Rh4 { [%cal Gh5h6,Gh6h7,Gh7h8] }) 29. Rd1 Rg8 30. g3 Rg4 31. Rd5+ Ke6 32. Kf3 Rg5 33. Kf4 (33. Rxg5 { Also winning, but less clear. } 33... fxg5 34. Kg4 h6 (34... Kf6 35. Kh5 b6 36. g4 $22) 35. Kh5 Ke5 36. Kxh6 Kxe4 37. Kxg5 { [%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5,Gh5h6,Gh6h7,Gh7h8] }) 33... Rxd5 (33... Re5 { Stiffer resistance. } 34. h4 { However, the inevitable zugzwang cannot be denied. }) 34. exd5+ Kf7 35. Kf5 h5 36. a4 a5 37. h3 b6 38. h4 { With zugzwang on the board, black resigned rather than allow the f and h pawns to fall by force. } *


