1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 a6 8. Qxc4 b5 9. Qc2 Bb7 10. Bg5 (10. Bd2! Be4 11. Qc1 Nc6!? { What I've decided is the most testing variation } 12. Nc3? Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Nxd4 14. Bxa8 Qxa8 $15) 10... Nbd7 11. a4 b4 12. Nbd2 c5 13. dxc5 Bxc5 $10 { With this break achieved, black should now have equality. } 14. Nc4 Rc8 15. Rfd1? Qe7? (15... Bd5 16. b3 Qc7 $17 { I was considering this line heavily, but I didn't want to obstruct the rook's vision of the queen. Apparently, the pin on my f6 knight is more important... }) 16. b3? (16. e3 h6 17. Bxf6 (17. Bf4?? Bxf3 18. Bxf3 e5!) 17... Nxf6 $10 { But black keeps the bishop pair and should be pushing }) 16... h6 17. Bf4 Be4 (17... Nb6 18. Nfe5 Nxc4 19. Nxc4 Bd5! { A move I did not even consider! } 20. Bxd5?? exd5 $19 { [%cal Gc5f2] }) 18. Qb2 Nd5 19. e3 Nc3 (19... f6! { Never play f6... But here the threat of g5 cannot be adequately handled. Stopping 3 pieces from using the e5 square is an added benefit, especially the trapped f4 bishop. }) 20. Bd6?? (20. Rd2 Nf6 (20... Bd5 { Better, although not what I had originally intended. }) 21. Bd6 Bxd6 22. Nxd6 Rc5 23. Nxe4 Nfxe4 $17) 20... Nxd1! 21. Bxe7 Nxb2 22. Bxc5 (22. Bxf8?! Nxc4 23. Bxc5 Nxc5 24. bxc4 b3 { While this is technically equal material, white is hopeless lost as the threat of b2-b1 is unstoppable. } 25. Nd2 b2 26. Ra2 b1=Q+ 27. Nxb1 Bxb1 $19) 22... Nxc5 23. Nxb2 Nxb3 24. Rd1 Rfd8 { No counterplay. The passed b pawn should win. } 25. Rf1 Rc2 (25... Bxf3 26. Bxf3 Nd2 27. Be2 Nxf1 28. Bxf1 Rc2 $19 { Also directly winning. }) 26. Nd1 Rc1 27. Nd4 (27. Nb2 Bxf3 28. Bxf3 Rxf1+ 29. Kxf1 Nd2+ 30. Ke2 Nxf3 31. Kxf3 $19 { What I had planned if white repeated. }) 27... Bxg2 28. Nxb3 Rcxd1 (28... Bxf1 29. Nxc1 Rxd1 $19 { A cleaner win... }) 29. Kxg2 Rxf1 30. Kxf1 Rd3 31. Nc5 Ra3 32. Ke2 (32. Nxa6?? b3 $19 { And the b pawn cannot be stopped. }) 32... b3 33. Kd3 b2+ 34. Kc2 Rc3+! 35. Kxc3 b1=Q $19 { White resigned a few moves later, down a queen. } *


