1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 Nbd7 4. Nf3 e5 5. Bc4 Be7 { Through the Philidor move-order, we arrive at a black lion. } 6. O-O c6 7. a4 { stopping b5 } 7... a5 (7... O-O!? 8. Re1 Qc7 9. h3 b6 10. Ba2 a6 { Another interesting setup, black plays for b5 at the right moment. }) 8. Re1 h6 9. Ba2! { I really like this prophylactic move, getting out of Nc5 sometimes with tempo, and basically forcing black to commit to the all-out kingside attack, or go with something more standard. } 9... Qc7 10. Qd3 Nf8 (10... O-O 11. h3 $14 { It's very hard to untangle black's pieces now. Black probably should go for b6+Bb7, but it's not as good with the pawn committed to a5. }) 11. Qc4! Bd8 (11... Be6? 12. d5! { This pin on the c file ensures the long diagonal towards black's king will stay open. } { [%cal Gc4c7] } 12... Bg4 13. dxc6 Be6 14. Nb5!! { I didn't see this in the game, but this is amazing: } (14. Nd5 $16 { I hadn't fully visualized this position, but this was my initial thought. White stands well. }) 14... Qb8 15. cxb7! Bxc4 16. bxa8=Q Qxa8 17. Nc7+ Kd7 18. Nxa8 $18) 12. Be3 Ng6?? (12... Ng4? 13. Rad1 Nxe3 14. Rxe3 Ne6 15. d5 Nf4 (15... cxd5 16. Qxd5! $18 { Dream Sicilian position against the backwards d pawn. }) 16. dxc6 Be6 $18 { Similar to the other line, white will have a huge attack. } 17. Nb5!! $18) (12... Ne6!? 13. h3 $14 { Not a crushing position, but white remains in firm control of this position. }) 13. dxe5 dxe5 14. Bb6! Qe7 (14... Qxb6?? 15. Qxf7#) 15. Bxd8 Kxd8 (15... Qxd8?? 16. Qxf7#) 16. Rad1+?? (16. Qxf7! Qxf7 17. Bxf7 $18 { In retrospect, this is completely winning, but I didn't appreciate how strong the endgame would be since I am already winning the e5 pawn next. } { [%csl Gg6,Ge5] }) 16... Ke8 { I couldn't believe it, but at this point I recognized that there's just no way to further the attack. Any slow move runs into Be6, after which I am forced back. Admitting that I'd already screwed up, I decided to keep building. } 17. Re3 Nf4?? (17... Be6 18. Qf1 Bxa2 19. Nxa2 $14 { The correct way forward is not that convincing. }) 18. Nxe5! { It took me a long time to pull the trigger on this, simply because I couldn't find the correct continuation as in the game. } 18... Be6 (18... Qxe5?? 19. Qxf7# { Revisiting the same theme. }) 19. Qd4! (19. Nxc6? Bxc4 20. Nxe7 Bxa2 21. Nf5 Be6 22. Nxg7+ Kf8 23. Nxe6+ Nxe6 $10 { I wanted to make this work for a long time, but I was unconvinced, rightfully so. The endgame is levelish as there's no passed pawn for white! }) 19... Bxa2 (19... c5 20. Qd6 $18 { It took me a while to clearly see this position from before Nxe5, but indeed this is safe for white. }) 20. Nxa2 Ne6 21. Qc3 Kf8 { White is safely up a pawn and can seek to consolidate before infiltrating on the queenside. } 22. Nc4 Kg8 23. f3 Kh7 24. Red3 Rhd8 (24... Nc5 25. Rd6 Nxa4?! 26. Qd4 { I thought this would be great for white, but the engine finds ways to make it messy: } 26... b5 27. b3 bxc4 28. bxa4 Rhb8 $16) 25. Nxa5?? { Too greedy! I hadn't fully consolidated, but I wanted to get my my a2 knight into the game potentially with Nb4. Taking the a5 pawn was a step towards that consolidation. It's simply mistimed... } (25. Rxd8 Rxd8 26. Rxd8 Qxd8 27. Qd2 Qxd2 28. Nxd2 $18 { White's best try. The knight will return to c4, targeting the queenside. For instance: } 28... Nd7 29. Nc4 b6 30. Nc1 Kg6 31. Ne2 Kf6 32. Kf2 Ke7 33. Ke3 Kd8 34. Nd4 Nxd4 35. Kxd4 Kc7 $18) 25... Nf4!! { White simply cannot parry the triple threat of Ne2+, Nd3+ and Qc5+ winning the a5 knight. } 26. Nc1! { The best try. "Always sacrifice the exchange" } (26. R3d2?? Ne2+ 27. Rxe2 Rxd1+ 28. Kf2 $19) (26. Rxd8?? Ne2+ 27. Kf1 Nxc3 28. Rxa8 Nxd1 $19) 26... Nxd3 27. Nxd3 { White's position is rotten, but not hopeless. Black is up the exchange, but the open d file is now irrelevant, the position is closed enough that the knight's can find solid squares, and white is up two pawns. Black is still better though because he can again take advantage of the undefended pieces. } 27... c5? { Reasonable, but now white can quickly defend everything. } (27... Qc7! 28. b4 c5! 29. Rb1 Ne8! 30. e5 cxb4 31. Qxc7 Nxc7 32. Nxb7 Rd4 33. Nd6 $15 { The position is a mess because white still hasn't fully solidified. }) 28. b3 Qc7 29. Nc4 { At this point, I felt comfortable enough with my position that I was at least equal. } 29... Ra6 30. Qd2 { Controlling the f4 square in some lines, and opposite black's rook which turns out to be a good thing... the positional idea of e5 cannot be stopped! } 30... Qe7 (30... Nh5!? 31. Re1! $16 { And Nf4 is stopped, with g4 to come soon. Black will be pushed back again. } (31. g4?? Nf4 $10 { [%cal Gd8d1] })) 31. e5! Nd5?? (31... Ne8 32. Qe3 f6 33. Re1 $16 { A sad position for black, but potentially his best try. }) 32. Nf4! { Who's pinning whom? } 32... Nxf4 33. Qxd8 Qe6 34. Rd2?! { I thought it was smart to pre-defend the g2 square, seeing Qg6 on the cards, but in fact this was not the way forward. } (34. Qd7 Qg6 35. Rd2 b5? 36. Qxb5 $18 { A much cleaner way forward. }) 34... b5! 35. axb5 Ra1+ 36. Kf2 Qg6 { I've broken the cardinal rule: "Thou shalt not allow counterplay," but my position should be solid enough that white is fine. I'm up 3 pawns, so giving away one or two is not a problem - all that matters is the king safety. } 37. g3 Nh3+ 38. Ke3! (38. Ke2?! Nf4+!? { I wasn't sure about this check, but in actual fact it's all fine too. } 39. gxf4 Qg2+ 40. Kd3! $18 (40. Ke3?? Re1+ 41. Kd3 Qxf3+ 42. Ne3 Rxe3+ 43. Kc4 Rc3#)) (38. Kg2?? Rg1+! 39. Kxh3 Qf5+ 40. Kh4 g5+ 41. Kh5 Qh3# $19) 38... Re1+ 39. Re2 Rxe2+ (39... Qxc2 { A funny try, but there's no threats here: } 40. Qd3+ Qxd3+ 41. Kxd3 $18 { [%cal Gb5b8] }) 40. Kxe2 Qxc2+ 41. Qd2! Qxb3 (41... Ng1+ 42. Ke3 Qxb3+ 43. Qd3+ $18 { Basically transposing to the game. }) 42. Qd3+! Qxd3+ 43. Kxd3 { And the b pawn cannot be stopped. } 43... Ng5 44. b6 Ne6 45. b7 $18 { Black resigned now. The poor move 27...c5? strikes again! Nc5+ here would save the game. } *


