1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5 4. d3 fxe4 5. dxe4 Nf6 6. O-O Bc5 7. Nc3?! (7. Qd3! { The main theoretical move stops castling. } 7... d6 (7... O-O?? 8. Qc4+ $18) 8. Qc4 { again stopping castling: } 8... Bd7 (8... Qe7?! 9. Nc3 Be6? 10. Nd5 $16) 9. Nc3 Qe7 10. Nd5 Nxd5 11. exd5 Nd4 12. Bxd7+ Qxd7 13. Nxe5! Qf5 14. Nd3 O-O-O { Black threatens b5!! trapping white's queen. } 15. a4 $14 { Mamedyarov, Shakhriyar - Radjabov, Teimour, 1/2-1/2, Baku FIDE GP, 2008, https://lichess.org/YfduHPOt }) 7... d6 8. Bg5 O-O 9. Nd5 Kh8 10. c3?! { A reasonable try, but now black gets in a maneuver he is looking forward to anyway. } (10. Nxf6 gxf6 11. Be3 Bxe3 12. fxe3 Ne7 $14 { The same position as in the game, but white has not wasted a tempo with c3. }) 10... Ne7! { Releases the pin on the f6 knight, and transfers to the kingside where it could help play f5 or potentially land on the f4 square. } 11. Nxf6 gxf6 12. Be3! { An excellent move that I'm quite proud of. } (12. Bh4?! { If you try retreating somewhere else, then black's center dominates. } 12... Ng6 13. Bg3 f5 14. exf5 Bxf5 $15) 12... Bxe3 13. fxe3 { The point is that black's central pawn mass can get out of control if left unattended. Now, the d5 and f5 pawn breaks are less appealing because either break allows white to undouble the pawns AND still white keeps a center. The open f file (and possibly d file) means white keeps dynamic play as well. } 13... c6 14. Bd3 { Keeping a close eye on the two pawn breaks again. } 14... Bg4 (14... d5 15. Nh4 $14 (15. exd5? cxd5 16. Nh4 f5 $15)) (14... Ng6 { An added benefit of having the e3 pawn: Nf4 is now never an issue. }) 15. Qe1 { Keeping an eye on e3 and transferring to the kingside. } 15... Qb6 16. b4!? { Possibly not necessary, but I saw the line that was played in the game and I thought it was nice to get play on all sides of the board. } (16. h3!? Be6 (16... Bxf3 17. Rxf3 Qxb2 18. Rb1 Qxa2 19. Rxb7 { I wanted to make this type of line work (and indeed it is), but black is not forced to take these pawns, and the insertion of h3 means the f3 rook can now never use the h3 square. }) 17. b3!) (16. b3!? a5 17. Nh4 a4 18. b4 { This seems like an improvement over the game, although the engine is unfazed and gives: } 18... Ng6! $10 { The point being: } 19. Nf5?! Nf4! $15) 16... a5 17. b5 Be6 18. bxc6 Qxc6?! (18... bxc6 { Correct. Black did not correctly assess the queenside activity is not going anywhere. } 19. Rb1 Qc5 { Not my favorite position to play, but the central pawns still favor white after: } 20. c4! $10 (20. Rb7 Ra7! $15)) 19. Nh4?! (19. c4! Rac8 (19... Bxc4? 20. Rc1 b5 21. Nd2 $16) 20. Rb1 Bxc4 21. Bxc4 Qxc4 22. Rxb7 $14) 19... Qc5 { Black tries to return to his previous missed idea, but at the cost of a tempo. Since the dynamics are on white's side, each tempo really does count. } 20. Rb1 b6 (20... Bxa2 21. Rxb7 Ra7 22. Rxa7 Qxa7 $10) 21. Rb5 Qc6 22. Rf2 { I am happy to trade the isolated c pawn in exchange for the b6 pawn and access to the 6th rank. Regardless, my two e pawns hold up black's 3 central pawns in all variations. } 22... Qxc3?? $18 { He hallucinated that the pawn was for some reason no longer defended, and immediately resigned. The position was still level after say: } (22... Rac8 23. Qe2 $10) *


