1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bd3 Bxd3 6. Qxd3 e6 7. Bg5 Qb6! { My 1600 lichess opponent plays the critical variation! } 8. Nd2 c5 9. c4 Ne7? { A reasonable try if you haven't seen this position before, but ultimately the f8 bishop will be a key problem piece. } (9... Qxb2 10. Rd1 Nc6 11. Ngf3 Nb4 12. Qe2 cxd4 13. O-O d3 14. Qe3 Qa3 15. Rb1 $10 { [%cal Gb1b3] }) 10. Ngf3 Nbc6 11. dxc5! (11. O-O!? cxd4 12. cxd5 Nxd5 13. Nc4 Qc7 14. a3 $14 { This type of a line seems to justify black's development. }) 11... Qxc5 12. O-O g6?? (12... O-O-O? { The move I was most expecting, but a mistake nonetheless: } 13. Rfc1 dxc4 14. Qe2 $18 { Castling into the attack is not going to work out for black. } { [%cal Gd2c4] }) 13. Rfd1? { In setting up a cheapo (Ne4!), I missed a much more natural win. } (13. Bf6! Rg8 $18 { With a crushing bind on the dark squares. }) 13... Bg7 14. cxd5 Qxd5 15. Qa3! { On the side of the board, the queen controls many key dark squares: d6, e7, f8. } 15... Bxe5? { Too greedy, but the position is probably already lost anyway with best play. } (15... Nf5 16. Rac1 Qa5 17. Qxa5 Nxa5 18. Rc7 O-O 19. Ne4 $18 { [%cal Gd1d7] }) 16. Nxe5 Qxe5 17. Nc4 Qc7 18. Qc3?! (18. Nd6+ Kf8 19. Nb5! { The move I missed. Now the attack plays itself out: } 19... Qe5 20. Bxe7+ Nxe7 21. Rd7 $18 { [%csl Ge7][%cal Ga1c1,Gc1c7] }) 18... Rf8?? (18... O-O 19. Bh6 Nf5 20. Bxf8 Rxf8 $16 { After best play, white is up a clear exchange and has more active pieces. }) 19. Nd6+ $18 { Once Kf8 is no longer possible, this check becomes all the more powerful. Black will have to give up the queen either this move or next after Nb5 discovered checks. Rather than play the rest out, my opponent resigned. } *


