1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Bd3 Nf6 6. O-O Qc7 7. c4 { I'm not 100% sure how this line differs from the other Maroczy. } (7. Qe2 d6 8. c4 { The most critical option in my opinion. }) 7... Bc5?! (7... Nc6!? { The main move. } 8. Nxc6 (8. Nf3 Ng4! 9. h3 h5 $10) 8... dxc6 9. f4 (9. Be3 e5 $10) 9... e5 $10) 8. Be3 O-O 9. Nb3? { It was at this point that I no longer thought my opponent was using an engine. } 9... Bxe3 10. fxe3 { Activates the rook, but this is just asking for a knight to land on the e4 and/or e5 squares. } 10... Nc6 11. Nc3 Ne5 12. Be2 b6 { [%csl Ge4] } 13. h3! (13. Qd4?! Neg4 $17 { And black creates real threats on the weakened dark squares. } { [%cal Gc7h2] }) 13... Bb7 14. Qd4 d6 { During the game, this seemed to me to be the world's best hedgehog. } 15. Rac1 Qc6?! { I thought it was smart to further pile up pressure on the e4 pawn, but I missed his response. } (15... Rfd8 $17 { A more sensible move. }) 16. Nd2 { In retrospect, this is just a move that white wanted to play anyway to free up the b pawn to push forward. Meanwhile, I know the queen is often misplaced on c6 in the hedgehog. } 16... Rfd8 17. Nf3 Nxe4? { Trading a center pawn for the b pawn. I thought that activating my b7 bishop was the way to go. Interestingly enough, the pressure on the e pawn is probably more important than the actual pawn. Now white's queen will be free to move about and I have nothing to show for it. } (17... Nfd7?! { My other idea is not impressive either. } 18. Rfd1 Nxf3+ 19. gxf3 Ne5 20. f4 $14) (17... Ned7 $15 { The engine insists I should just play it slow and keep all the trumps in the position. Probably reposition the queen to c7 again. } { [%cal Gc6c7] }) 18. Nxe4 (18. Nxe5? dxe5 (18... Nxc3?? 19. Nxc6 Nxe2+ 20. Kf2 Nxd4 21. Nxd8 $18) 19. Qxe4 Qxe4 20. Nxe4 Bxe4 $17) 18... Qxe4 19. Qxb6 Rac8 (19... Nd7 20. Qd4 { I couldn't see how this would help me. }) 20. b4! { Only now did I see how foolish this transformation was. White's queenside pawns are a long term asset if I ever trade queens. Meanwhile, do I really have anything on the kingside? } 20... h5? { Feigning at a g5-g4 threat. I was really feeling like I had to do something immediately on the kingside. } (20... h6 21. Rf2 Nd7 22. Qd4 Qc6 $10 { Much more sensible. My pieces are still good and the queenside pawns can't roll themselves without support. }) 21. Rf2 { Stopping the threat before it ever materializes. } 21... Rd7 { Now Nxc4 is a threat. } (21... Nxc4?? 22. Bxc4 Rxc4 23. Rxc4 Qxc4 24. Qxd8+ $18) 22. Nxe5! Qxe5 (22... dxe5?? { The move you want to play to avoid any and all weaknesses fails. } 23. Bf3 $18 { [%cal Gf3b7] }) 23. Qd4! { Maybe I'm just too paranoid, but it was at this move that I began to suspect my opponent was using an engine again. White had navigated this middlegame brilliantly even with a worse structure, and I'm not used to missing this many moves from my opponent in a row. } 23... Qg5 (23... Qxd4? 24. exd4 $16 { Now the queenside pawn pushes play themselves. A queen trade would be a poor choice even if it didn't help out white's structure. }) (23... Rdc7? 24. Rd1 Qxd4 25. exd4 $16) 24. Bf1 e5 { What I felt was a sad necessity. Puts the pawns on dark squares when there are two light squared bishops. Moreover, the white queen cannot be allowed to dominate from d4. Until this point, I really wanted my queen to dominate from e5... } 25. Qd2 Rcc7! { Everything should be off a light square. } 26. a4 Qg6? 27. Rd1! { I had believed the rook was well placed on c1 behind the soon-to-be passed c5 pawn. But actually the pawns kill all my pieces on the queenside anyway, so there's no rush to open it up. } (27. Bd3 Be4 { I wanted to meet white's potential bishop activation with an offer to trade queens. Once again, I want my queen to re-enter the center on e4. } 28. Bxe4? (28. Bf1 $16) 28... Qxe4 $10) 27... Rd8 28. c5 a5? { A desperate attempt to break up the queenside. } 29. cxd6 (29. bxa5?? Rxc5 $16) (29. b5 Rxc5 30. Qxa5 Rdc8 $18 { I figured I could fight on here too, but these two pawns are killer. }) 29... Rcd7 30. Qc3 Rxd6 31. Rxd6 Qxd6 32. bxa5 Ra8 33. Bc4! $18 { I spent a long time looking for any type of active defense. But ultimately with literally the only move being Rf8 here, I decided to resign. } 33... Rc8? (33... Bd5?? 34. Qd3! $18) (33... Rf8 34. Qb3 $18 { Better pieces. Extra a pawns. Safer king. }) 34. Bxf7+ Kh8 35. Qb3 $18 *


